Aurora Serverless, Global Database, and Backtrack.

Aurora Serverless v2 auto-scales a cluster's compute capacity in real time, in fine-grained increments, based on actual load. The unit is the Aurora Capacity Unit, or A-C-U, roughly two gigabytes of R-A-M plus proportional C-P-U and network, and it scales in half-A-C-U steps, in seconds, without dropping connections. You set a minimum and maximum A-C-U range. Unlike the deprecated v1, which paused and resumed by replacing the instance, with connection drops and a ten-second-plus warmup, v2 scales the live instance, so the application sees no break. It fits variable or unpredictable workloads, dev and test clusters, and multi-tenant SaaS, and it can mix with provisioned instances in one cluster.

Aurora Global Database spans multiple regions as a single logical cluster: one primary region accepts writes, and up to five secondary regions accept reads, replicated at the storage layer with sub-second lag across continents. The disaster-recovery headline is the strong part: an R-P-O, or data loss, of under one second, and an R-T-O, or recovery time, of under one minute, via managed planned failover, plus an unplanned manual detach if the primary region is fully unreachable. It's the strongest cross-region relational option and the standard pattern for global low-latency reads.

Aurora Backtrack rewinds an Aurora MySQL cluster to a previous point in time in place, without restoring from a snapshot, creating a new instance, or changing the endpoint, within a window configurable up to seventy-two hours, in seconds, because Aurora's storage layer keeps a continuous change log. The use case: somebody just ran delete-from-customers without a where clause; backtrack five minutes, and all is well. It's Aurora MySQL only. There's also Aurora Multi-Master, with multiple writers, but it's niche and legacy; the standard single-writer with fast failover is right for almost every workload.
